1 (i) the availability of an adequate water supply;
2 (ii) the presence and response capability of a professional fire
3 department;
4 (iii) the practicability or feasibility of compliance with modern fire
5 codes, including a comparison to the safety of the existing housing supply;
6 (iv) the practicability or feasibility of building in urban or infill
7 settings;
8 (v) the viability of redevelopment or adaptive reuse of historic
9 properties;
10 (vi) any impacts of laws, ordinances, or policies on:
11 1. housing development; or
12 2. the cost of housing; and
13 (vii) any other relevant factors, as determined by the Department;
14 and
15 (3) make legislative and regulatory recommendations, including potential
16 amendments to the Maryland Building Performance Standards, to authorize the
17 construction of single–staircase buildings up to six stories above grade plane in the State
18 for the purpose of increasing the affordable housing supply by reducing barriers to
19 multifamily housing development.
20 (d) In carrying out the study, the Department shall consult with:
21 (1) a fire engineer who is a faculty member at a public institution of higher
22 education that has a fire protection program; and
23 (2) a representative of a union that represents firefighters.
24 (e) On or before December 1, 2025, the Department shall report its findings and
25 recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State
26 Government Article, the General Assembly, the Senate Education, Energy, and the
27 Environment Committee, and the House Environment and Transportation Committee.
28 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
29 1, 2025.

